‘The sea is ours’: Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol an armored boat in the naval headquarters of La Paz.
Public buildings fly a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motorcycle: “The sea is ours by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout the blockade of Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still very much present, as is the desire to sail on the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, for Bolivia is awaiting a decision of the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of the Bolivian request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be required to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who is facing a controversial re-election fight next year), also has much to say about the decision to be made on Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Chile, and that little would change, even if the decision were positive.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice renders its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from favoring the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have even harmed it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ bellicose rhetoric undermined all remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to trade, but after that it will be very difficult to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court’s decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales – who remains to this day one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The Court’s decision is an opportunity to see that we must get rid of the past.”
