John Edward: Language skills are essential for citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this trend continued in 2018 with new excellent exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they have chosen and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector able to design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
If we look at the excellent results in the exams this year, we find that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates among independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages scored the highest grade, A.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, show that 72% of students scored the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as did the 72% of students who studied German, the 69% of students who studied French and the 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and youth in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organized just like science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 UK Employment and Skills Commission survey found that of the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job openings requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of their career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this lasting skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them did not have sufficient command of a foreign language to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking multiple languages, including those in emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of them will focus on contemporary classical languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the 2020s, including Mandarin and Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to offer a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is clear that today, in a global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
