North Korea says that disarmament cannot be done “under any circumstances” unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that continuing sanctions strengthened its distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
At the annual General Assembly of the world body, Ri Yong Ho said that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, it is excluded that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While reiterating North Korea’s well-known criticisms of Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, his statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work toward a “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking to formally end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected requests to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and accentuates the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, even opposing the "declaration of the end of war".
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us fall don’t know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our distrust.”
Ri made no comment about the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations by the American leader earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, and added: “If the party concerned by the issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he declared before the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after the “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened at the United Nations last year to “totally destroy” North Korea, did not laud this year the courage with which Kim applied measures towards disarmament, but added that much remained to be done and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set. “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the application of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly and then announced that he would travel again to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying progress had been made, but in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced his “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts towards a normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights against the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
A professor has noticed that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of themselves
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
At the end, a student came up to me and said, "Why am I only told that in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Taught for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map featuring interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not instantly change students’ behavior.
However, in our view, they have the right to know this information – in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the pride culture of “sleeping at night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having enough and good quality sleep should be students' "secret weapon" to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode, making them starving permanently.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar program of study before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up times, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disturbances.
