Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now, a page from our Sunday Morning Almanac: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE COMPUTER TOURNE... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that later gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as seen in the 1950 film “Bells of Coronado,” starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man asks, “What is this?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, we use it to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
“Thanks to these headphones, we can actually hear the effects of atoms released into minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “Tell me, it’s definitely jumping out there!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
New Cancer Vaccine Allows the Immune System to ‘Detect’ Cancer Cells
New Cancer Vaccine Allows the Immune System to ‘Detect’ Cancer Cells and Kill Them
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory
They can then “detect” a protein that is common to many cancers, and are then reinjected
An experimental vaccine shows encouraging results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who received the vaccine, whose goal is to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory, so that they can detect the HER2 protein common to many cancers, and finally re-inject them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the US National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine.”
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein “causes an increase in several types of cancer”, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers.
A similar approach, which involves taking immune cells to “teach” them to target cancer cells, has been proven to be effective in treating a type of leukemia.
