For example, BMW says it will close its Mini plant in Oxford for a month following Brexit.
The biggest concerns are about what car manufacturers call supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is operated in "tensioned flow", parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers in the UK and the EU for custom-made vehicles.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, there could be disturbances at the border that, according to the industry, could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to hold inventory for more than a day at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, and therefore production would be stopped.
According to Clark, Theresa May’s Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is “precisely calibrated to avoid these border controls.”
