Red Tide Info Point: Decline in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Concentrations
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - leading to fears of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are islets about 10 miles (16 km) off Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, medium concentrations off Charlotte County and low concentrations off the bottom of this county.
Respiratory irritation persists in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwest Florida during the past week.
